Here's a JavaScript function that creates a "Forgot Password" page and handles password reset:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Forgot Password</title>
    <style>
        .forgot-password {
            text-align: center;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 300px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .confirm-button {
            display: none;
            background-color: #6c757d;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="forgot-password">
        <h2>Forgot Password?</h2>
        <p>Enter your email address to reset your password.</p>
        <a href="#" id="forgotPassword">Forgot Password Link</a>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Function to handle "Forgot Password" link click
        function showPassword() {
            // Remove existing password fields
            document.querySelectorAll('input[name="password"]').forEach(input => {
                input.remove();
            });

            // Show new password field
            const newPassword = document.createElement('input');
            newPassword.type = 'password';
            newPassword.placeholder = 'Enter new password';
            document.body.appendChild(newPassword);

            // Show confirmation button for resetting password again
            const confirmButton = document.createElement('button');
            confirmButton.textContent = 'Reset Password Again';
            confirmButton.style.display = 'none';
            confirmButton.addEventListener('click', showPasswordAgain);
            document.body.appendChild(confirmButton);

            // Show new password field
            const newPassword2 = document.createElement('input');
            newPassword2.type = 'password';
            newPassword2.placeholder = 'Confirm new password';
            document.body.appendChild(newPassword2);

            return true;
        }

        function showPasswordAgain(event) {
            event.preventDefault();

            const emailInput = document.querySelector('input[type="text"]');
            const newPassword = document.querySelector('input[name="newPassword"]');
            const newPassword2 = document.querySelector('input[name="confirmNewPassword"]');
            const button = document.querySelector('.confirm-button');

            if (newPassword.value && newPassword2.value) {
                // Here you would typically make an API call to update the password
                alert('Reset password process started. Please wait...');

                function resetPassword(email, newPassword) {
                    // Replace this with actual API call
                    console.log(`Reset password for ${email} to ${newPassword}`);

                    // Show success message
                    document.querySelector('input[type="text"]').value = 'Reset successful!';
                    document.querySelector('input[name="newPassword"]').disabled = true;
                    document.querySelector('input[name="confirmNewPassword"]').disabled = true;
                    button.style.display = 'block';
                }

                resetPassword(emailInput.value, newPassword.value);
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a "Forgot Password" page that:

1. Shows an input field for the email address
2. Shows two password fields (one to reset and one to confirm)
3. Has a confirmation button to reset the password again

When the user clicks the confirmation button, it sends both the old and new passwords through your application.

Note: This is just the frontend part of the function. You'll need to add backend logic for:

1. Verifying the email address
2. Resetting the password (this would typically involve a database call)
3. Security measures like two-factor authentication

Make sure to:
- Use HTTPS in your browser
- Keep sensitive information like passwords encrypted
- Securely handle API calls when implementing this on a real website
